<hr />
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="floatright">
<div><a href="/wiki/File:Biological_classification_L_Pengo.svg" title="Enlarge"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/6b/Magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" border="0" /></a></div>
</div>
The hierarchy of <a href="/wiki/Biological_classification" title="Biological classification">biological classification</a>'s major eight <a href="/wiki/Taxonomic_rank" title="Taxonomic rank">taxonomic ranks</a>. A <a href="/wiki/Genus" title="Genus">genus</a> contains one or more species. Intermediate minor rankings are not shown.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>In <a href="/wiki/Biology" title="Biology">biology</a>, a <b>species</b> is one of the basic units of <a href="/wiki/Biological_classification" title="Biological classification">biological classification</a> and a <a href="/wiki/Taxonomic_rank" title="Taxonomic rank">taxonomic rank</a>. A species is often defined as a group of organisms capable of interbreeding and producing fertile offspring. While in many cases this definition is adequate, more precise or differing measures are often used, such as based on similarity of DNA or morphology. Presence of specific locally adapted traits may further subdivide species into <a href="/wiki/Subspecies" title="Subspecies">subspecies</a>.</p>
